{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620910"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:47:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:47:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16652"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16652","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16652"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.62,0.12,0.08,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9343"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66141"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9343","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9343"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16652"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51598"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5063"},{"type":"tags","id":"5065"},{"type":"tags","id":"8120"},{"type":"tags","id":"10133"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22127"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22128"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66141"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman with heart failure is prescribed spironolactone. Her doctor explains that regular monitoring of potassium levels will be required.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes their primary mechanism of action ?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduced renin release from the kidney","Competitive inhibition of mineralocorticoid receptors","Stimulation of potassium secretion in the distal tubule","Blocked sodium channels in the collecting duct","Inhibition of aldosterone synthesis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECommon examples of aldosterone receptor antagonists include spironolactone and eplerenone. They work by \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompetitively inhibiting mineralocorticoid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E in the distal tubule and collecting duct of the kidney. This prevents aldosterone from binding to these receptors, reducing sodium and water reabsorption while increasing potassium retention; this potassium-sparing effect means that serum potassium levels must be carefully monitored during treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReducing renin release from the kidney\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as these drugs may actually increase renin release through feedback mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulating potassium secretion in the distal tubule\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect as these drugs actually reduce potassium secretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocking sodium channels in the collecting duct\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of action of amiloride, not aldosterone receptor antagonists.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAldosterone receptor antagonists do not \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibit aldosterone synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Aldosterone receptor antagonists competitively block mineralocorticoid receptors in the distal tubule and collecting duct of the kidney.","Blocking aldosterone receptors increases sodium and water excretion while reducing potassium excretion.","Spironolactone and eplerenone are the main aldosterone receptor antagonists used clinically."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51598"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16652"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51598"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T12:14:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T09:17:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9343"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66141"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/ta